I am new to object detection in general. I am working in a Linux environment on my local machine. I have tried following the steps in the YOLOv8 Training and Conversion to RKNN - Team 5990 TRIGON collab notebook translating it into a local python environment and using that team’s Cones-and-Cubes dataset. Once I get my model trained I can verify that my trained model is working using the model(images) results.show() because I can see the bounding boxes correctly drawn around the cubes on my monitor with a high confidence level (I don’t use any cones for testing). I convert the trained model and quantize for i8 and exported to rknn as shown in the collab. But the uploaded model to my Orange Pi 5 Pro does not recognize the cubes. I don’t know if the problem is the resolution settings on my LifeCam or the area/ratio sliders are wrong although I played with them all. There is no debug output from Photonvision that could help me figure out if the model I uploaded is being used when I select it. I am not sure how to proceed from here to get a working model.

In the rknn_model_zoo (on the OrangePI using my own Ubuntu 22.04.5 LTS install) I used this to convert:

python convert.py best.onnx rk3588 i8 yolo5n.rknn

I used this to run the test:

python yolov5.py --model_path yolo5n.rknn --target rk3588 --img_folder /home/orangepi/yolo/images --img_save

Here is the result image. I think the labels are coming from the COCO dataset and the anchors are from the rknn_model_zoo directory, as loaded by the yolov5.py script. I don’t know if the default anchors would have any effect when it comes to PhotonVision. I don’t really understand the concept of anchors and role they play. Also, I should mention that I trained with very few images but an epoch of 500 because I just want to see if I can get everything right to try my model in PhotonVision. The original Ultralytics model was yolov5s.yaml but here I renamed it yolo5n. Not sure if the naming would matter.

test1_640_640640×640 60.3 KB

I did retrain on the v5 model just to see if another version would work better. I just found that if I bring the confidence slider to zero PhotonVision starts to recognize my objects. But with that low a confidence it recognizes many things in the scene, most of them incorrect. Now I have to figure out why the PhotonVision confidence levels are so much lower than I got show in the image from my last post using the model zoo python script. How is PhotonVision interacting with the model differently than when I use the RockChip model zoo example? I was using the yolov5 model zoo to test my model before I installed it in PhotonVision.

ok so I got my model to work with training a yolo11n model. There was an extra step required using the ultralytics_yolo11 repository from airockchip. That step simplifies the custom trained yolo11n.pt model coming out of Ultralytics and creates the onnx version. Then when the model is converted to RKNN using the rknn_model_zoo it works in Photonvision. See this ultralytics_yolo11/RKOPT_README.md at main · airockchip/ultralytics_yolo11 · GitHub
